 Who was thankful for the invention of an umbrella today?

8
00:00:31,680 --> 00:00:35,440
 The World Wide Web Internet as we know it.

9
00:00:35,440 --> 00:00:40,680
 I mean, sometimes we may not be thankful, but I think the majority of us would say technology

10
00:00:40,680 --> 00:00:46,720
 has advanced at incredible paces, and if you're watching online, you get to benefit with that

11
00:00:46,720 --> 00:00:48,520
 as well today.

12
00:00:48,520 --> 00:00:57,600
 Well, one of my favorite inventions has to be the Kindle.

13
00:00:57,600 --> 00:00:58,920
 I love the Kindle.

14
00:00:58,920 --> 00:01:05,000
 Now I know all of you book lovers out there, you know, the ones that like to touch and

15
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,120
 feel and smell the pages.

16
00:01:07,120 --> 00:01:10,160
 Yes, yes, I know, we're getting nods here.

17
00:01:10,160 --> 00:01:12,360
 Heather Rose, I know you're watching online.

18
00:01:12,360 --> 00:01:14,560
 I know you love your books as well.

19
00:01:14,560 --> 00:01:21,840
 Well, I love the books, the Kindles, especially living in Hong Kong, because you know what

20
00:01:21,840 --> 00:01:23,920
 it's like if we have too many books?

21
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:25,480
 Where do we put them?

22
00:01:25,480 --> 00:01:31,080
 So with a Kindle, you can have hundreds of books, and you do not have to worry about

23
00:01:31,080 --> 00:01:34,320
 storage, right?

24
00:01:34,320 --> 00:01:43,320
 I love my Kindle because I love reading, and I love stories, and stories can be powerful

25
00:01:43,320 --> 00:01:51,000
 tools that really do shape how we think and how we view the world.

26
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:55,200
 Think of your favorite movie or book.

27
00:01:55,200 --> 00:02:01,000
 When you're immersed in that book or that movie, and you are so engrossed with what's

28
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:07,120
 happening, you have no idea what's happening outside of that book or that movie, and your

29
00:02:07,120 --> 00:02:11,840
 brain is telling you that you are part of that story.

30
00:02:11,840 --> 00:02:14,840
 Well, there is a term for this.

31
00:02:14,840 --> 00:02:18,520
 It's called narrative transportation theory.

32
00:02:18,520 --> 00:02:20,240
 Did you know that?

33
00:02:20,240 --> 00:02:21,240
 It's true.

34
00:02:21,240 --> 00:02:24,120
 It's amazing what you learn here in church.

35
00:02:24,120 --> 00:02:26,920
 Narrative transportation theory, seriously.

36
00:02:26,920 --> 00:02:35,400
 This suggests that the power of stories can actually change attitudes and intentions that

37
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:39,000
 are reflected in the story.

38
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:43,360
 I am 100% convinced this is true.

39
